  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Yinghu Pavilion in Fuzhou
  author: Cai Hongzhe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Though in life I've wandered far through seas and mountains,
    Here the spirit transcends the world—and deepens still.
    At first I thought I dreamed through clouds and rain-wreathed gorges,
    Then gradually felt my body enter into painted silk.
    Autumn nights on the southern river bring ten thousand peaks of moonlight,
    Spring winds in the northern quarter scatter flowers across all the trees.
    But even the most detached wanderer, free from worldly care,
    Cannot here remain unmoved—like driftwood carved clean of feeling.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yinghu Pavilion (映湖樓) is a pavilion in Fuzhou overlooking Yinghu Lake, known for its scenic beauty.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'clouds and rain-wreathed gorges' (云雨峡) alludes to a classical Chinese myth of divine lovers meeting in mountain realms.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The contrast between the detached ''dry driftwood'' (枯槎) of the final lines and the pavilion''s overwhelming beauty creates the poem''s paradox: even those who have transcended worldly attachment cannot help but be moved.'
